<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="52" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="21" pageNumber="52">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="21" pageNumber="52">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megachile cleomis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cleomis">Megachile cleomis</taxonomicName>
is one of the synonyms of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megachile texana" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="texana">Megachile texana</taxonomicName>
. It was originally described by Cockerell in 
<bibRefCitation author="Cockerell, TDA" journalOrPublisher="The Annals and Magazine of Natural History" pageId="22" pageNumber="53" pagination="13 - 15" title="The New Mexico bees of the Genus Megachile and a new Andrena." volume="6" year="1900">1900</bibRefCitation>
, based on two cotypes from a locality in New Mexico, a male and a female. The male was later found to be a male 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megachile snowi" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="snowi">Megachile snowi</taxonomicName>
. The female is herein designated as the lectotype for 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megachile cleomis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cleomis">Megachile cleomis</taxonomicName>
, which remains in synonymy with 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megachile texana" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="texana">Megachile texana</taxonomicName>
. This situation illustrates the importance of correctly assigning holotypes. 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megachile texana" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="texana">Megachile texana</taxonomicName>
is a widespread species which is found across North America (Figure 17).
</paragraph>
